<meta content="The nit-picking glory of The New Yorker's Comma Queen" itemprop='name'>
<meta content='"Copy editing for The New Yorker is like playing shortstop for a Major League Baseball team — every little movement gets picked over by the critics," says Mary Norris, who has played the position for more than thirty years. In that time, she&#x0027;s gotten a reputation for sternness and for being a "comma maniac," but this is unfounded, she says. Above all, her work is aimed at one thing: making authors look good. Explore The New Yorker&#x0027;s distinctive style with the person who knows it best in this charming talk.' itemprop='description'>
